and how to conquer it, so to speak.

00:06:54.840 --> 00:06:57.963
Let's start off very basic, what is sleep?

00:06:59.400 --> 00:07:03.080
- Sleep is probably the
single most effective thing

00:07:03.080 --> 00:07:05.500
you can do to reset your
brain and body health.

00:07:05.500 --> 00:07:08.720
So that's a functional
answer in terms of, you know,

00:07:08.720 --> 00:07:11.950
what is sleep in terms of its benefits.

00:07:11.950 --> 00:07:13.890
Sleep as a process though,

00:07:13.890 --> 00:07:18.710
is an incredibly complex
physiological ballet.

00:07:18.710 --> 00:07:20.530
And if you were to recognize

00:07:20.530 --> 00:07:22.330
or see what happens to your brain

00:07:22.330 --> 00:07:24.860
and your body at night, during sleep,

00:07:24.860 --> 00:07:26.940
you would be blown away.

00:07:26.940 --> 00:07:28.750
And the paradox is that most of us,

00:07:28.750 --> 00:07:30.750
and I would think this too, you know,

00:07:30.750 --> 00:07:32.440
if I wasn't a sleep scientist,

00:07:32.440 --> 00:07:37.380
we go to bed, we lose consciousness
for seven to nine hours,

00:07:37.380 --> 00:07:39.220
and then we sort of
wake up in the morning,

00:07:39.220 --> 00:07:41.570
and we generally feel better.

00:07:41.570 --> 00:07:43.930
And in some ways that denies

00:07:43.930 --> 00:07:48.260
the physiological and
biological beauty of sleep.

00:07:48.260 --> 00:07:49.940
So upstairs in your brain,

00:07:49.940 --> 00:07:52.447
when you're going through these
different stages of sleep,

00:07:52.447 --> 00:07:55.160
the changes in brainwave activity

00:07:55.160 --> 00:07:58.080
are far more dramatic
than those that we see

00:07:58.080 --> 00:07:59.007
when we're awake.

00:07:59.007 --> 00:08:01.970
And we can speak about deep
sleep and what happens there,

00:08:01.970 --> 00:08:03.950
REM sleep is a fascinating time,

00:08:03.950 --> 00:08:05.960
which is another stage of sleep,

00:08:05.960 --> 00:08:07.300
often called dream sleep,

00:08:07.300 --> 00:08:09.530
which is rapid eye movement sleep,

00:08:09.530 --> 00:08:11.650
that stage of sleep
some parts of your brain

00:08:11.650 --> 00:08:15.650
are up to 30%, more active
than when you're awake.

00:08:15.650 --> 00:08:18.280
So again, it's kind of violating this idea

00:08:18.280 --> 00:08:20.580
that our mind is dormant.

00:08:20.580 --> 00:08:24.510
And our body is just simply
quiescent and resting.

00:08:24.510 --> 00:08:26.840
So I would happy to just
sort of double click

00:08:26.840 --> 00:08:28.810
on either one of those,

00:08:28.810 --> 00:08:30.640
and also what changes in the body as well.

00:08:30.640 --> 00:08:32.700
But it is an intense

00:08:32.700 --> 00:08:36.867
evolutionary adaptive benefit and system.

00:08:36.867 --> 00:08:38.230
That said, though,

00:08:38.230 --> 00:08:43.230
I would almost push back
against an evolved system

00:08:43.650 --> 00:08:47.450
when we think about the question
of sleep and what sleep is.

00:08:47.450 --> 00:08:52.340
Our assumption has always
been that we evolved to sleep.

00:08:52.340 --> 00:08:53.710
And I've actually questioned that

00:08:53.710 --> 00:08:56.640
and I have no way to get in a time capsule

00:08:56.640 --> 00:08:57.870
and go back and prove this,

00:08:57.870 --> 00:09:02.400
but what if we started off sleeping,

00:09:02.400 --> 00:09:05.800
and it was from sleep,
that wakefulness emerged?

00:09:05.800 --> 00:09:09.070
Why do we assume that
it's the other way around?

00:09:09.070 --> 00:09:10.700
And I think there's probably

00:09:10.700 --> 00:09:12.610
some really good evidence

00:09:12.610 --> 00:09:16.020
that sleep may have been the proto state,

00:09:16.020 --> 00:09:20.170
that it was the basic
fundamental living state.

00:09:20.170 --> 00:09:23.540
And when we became awake, as it were,

00:09:23.540 --> 00:09:26.683
we always had to return to sleep.

00:09:26.683 --> 00:09:28.350
You know, in some ways, at that point,

00:09:28.350 --> 00:09:31.940
sleep was the price that
we paid for wakefulness.

00:09:31.940 --> 00:09:35.110
And that's another way of
describing what sleep is.

00:09:35.110 --> 00:09:37.203
But again, I think it sort of denies

00:09:37.203 --> 00:09:39.450
that the active state of sleep,

00:09:39.450 --> 00:09:42.446
it's not a passive state of sleep either.

00:09:42.446 --> 00:09:44.220
And then finally, you can say

00:09:44.220 --> 00:09:47.170
what is sleep across different species?

00:09:47.170 --> 00:09:48.940
And in us human beings,

00:09:48.940 --> 00:09:52.260
and in all mammalian species
and avian species as well,

00:09:52.260 --> 00:09:55.570
sleep is broadly separated
into these two main types.

00:09:55.570 --> 00:09:58.440
And we've got non rapid eye
movement sleep on the one hand,

00:09:58.440 --> 00:10:01.580
and then we've got rapid eye
movement sleep on the other.

00:10:01.580 --> 00:10:03.960
And we can speak about how they unfold

00:10:03.960 --> 00:10:06.010
across a night and their architecture

00:10:06.010 --> 00:10:09.060
because it's not just
intellectually interesting

00:10:09.060 --> 00:10:11.630
from the perspective of what sleep is,

00:10:11.630 --> 00:10:15.250
it's also practically
impactful for our daily lives.

00:10:15.250 --> 00:10:17.130
And I'd love to sort of
go down that route too.

00:10:17.130 --> 00:10:18.697
But you navigate, you tell me I can.

00:10:18.697 --> 00:10:20.610
- No, no, let's definitely
go down that route.

00:10:20.610 --> 00:10:23.300
So you mentioned how active the brain is,

00:10:23.300 --> 00:10:25.530
during certain phases of sleep.

00:10:25.530 --> 00:10:27.800
When I was coming up in science,

00:10:27.800 --> 00:10:29.800
REM sleep, rapid eye movement sleep

00:10:29.800 --> 00:10:32.210
was referred to as paradoxical sleep,

00:10:32.210 --> 00:10:34.310
is that still a good
way to think about it?

00:10:34.310 --> 00:10:36.190
Paradoxical because
the brain is so active,

00:10:36.190 --> 00:10:38.840
and yet we are essentially
paralyzed, correct?

00:10:38.840 --> 00:10:40.520
- Yeah, it really is a paradox.

00:10:40.520 --> 00:10:42.570
And where that came from

00:10:42.570 --> 00:10:45.130
was simply the brainwave recordings,

00:10:45.130 --> 00:10:47.480
that if all I'm measuring about you,

00:10:47.480 --> 00:10:50.120
is your brainwave activity,

00:10:50.120 --> 00:10:52.010
it's very difficult for me

00:10:52.010 --> 00:10:54.730
sitting outside of the
sleep laboratory room

00:10:54.730 --> 00:10:56.894
to figure out, are you awake,

00:10:56.894 --> 00:10:58.510
or are you in REM sleep?

00:10:58.510 --> 00:11:00.690
Because those two
patterns of brain activity

00:11:00.690 --> 00:11:02.900
are so close to one another,

00:11:02.900 --> 00:11:05.540
you can't discriminate between them.

00:11:05.540 --> 00:11:08.200
Yet, the paradox is
that when you are awake,

00:11:08.200 --> 00:11:10.630
I go in there and you're
sort of sitting up,

00:11:10.630 --> 00:11:12.780
you're clearly conscious and awake.

00:11:12.780 --> 00:11:15.280
But yet, when you go into REM sleep,

00:11:15.280 --> 00:11:18.337
you are completely paralyzed.

00:11:18.337 --> 00:11:23.240
And that's one of the I think
that's part of the paradox.

00:11:23.240 --> 00:11:25.580
But the paradox really just comes down to

00:11:25.580 --> 00:11:29.040
two dramatically different
conscious states.

00:11:29.040 --> 00:11:32.400
Yet, brain activity is dramatically

00:11:32.400 --> 00:11:34.230
more similar than different.

00:11:34.230 --> 00:11:35.820
And the way I can figure out

00:11:35.820 --> 00:11:37.950
which of the two you are in

00:11:37.950 --> 00:11:40.090
is by measuring two other signals,

00:11:40.090 --> 00:11:41.910
the activity from your eyes

00:11:41.910 --> 00:11:44.470
