And that's why you can have some people

00:58:56.490 --> 00:58:58.860
who are very sensitive to caffeine

00:58:58.860 --> 00:59:00.570
and other people who say, you know,

00:59:00.570 --> 00:59:02.780
it just doesn't affect me
really that much at all.

00:59:02.780 --> 00:59:04.550
- These are the people
that have a double espresso

00:59:04.550 --> 00:59:07.210
after a 9pm dinner and
can sleep just fine.

00:59:07.210 --> 00:59:08.950
- Well, and we'll come onto.

00:59:08.950 --> 00:59:09.949
- Well at least subjectively

00:59:09.949 --> 00:59:11.030
they think they are sleeping.

00:59:11.030 --> 00:59:12.770
- Subjectively, yeah,
and we should speak about

00:59:12.770 --> 00:59:14.840
that assumptive danger too.

00:59:14.840 --> 00:59:18.360
So then the caffeine is in the system

00:59:18.360 --> 00:59:20.160
and after some time period,

00:59:20.160 --> 00:59:23.470
it will be inactive in the system.

00:59:23.470 --> 00:59:24.720
So let's say that, you know,

00:59:24.720 --> 00:59:27.240
I've been awake for 12 hours now.

00:59:27.240 --> 00:59:29.890
And it's you know, 8pm

00:59:29.890 --> 00:59:31.180
and I'm feeling a bit tired,

00:59:31.180 --> 00:59:33.690
but I want to push through
and I want to keep working

00:59:33.690 --> 00:59:35.020
for another couple of hours,

00:59:35.020 --> 00:59:36.640
so I have a cup of coffee.

00:59:36.640 --> 00:59:38.700
All of a sudden I was feeling tired,

00:59:38.700 --> 00:59:41.820
but I don't feel like I've been
awake for 12 hours anymore.

00:59:41.820 --> 00:59:43.930
Because with the caffeine in the system,

00:59:43.930 --> 00:59:46.510
maybe only half of that adenosine

00:59:46.510 --> 00:59:50.530
is being communicated through
the receptor to my brain.

00:59:50.530 --> 00:59:53.110
100% of the adenosine is still there,

00:59:53.110 --> 00:59:55.430
only half of it is allowed
to communicate to my brain.

00:59:55.430 --> 00:59:58.014
So now I think oh I haven't
been awake for 12 hours,

00:59:58.014 --> 01:00:00.390
I've just been awake for
six hours, I feel great.

01:00:00.390 --> 01:00:02.050
Then after a few hours,

01:00:02.050 --> 01:00:05.130
and the caffeine is starting
to come out of my system,

01:00:05.130 --> 01:00:09.260
not only am I hit with the
same levels of adenosine

01:00:09.260 --> 01:00:11.980
that I had before I'd
had the cup of coffee

01:00:11.980 --> 01:00:13.330
several hours ago,

01:00:13.330 --> 01:00:16.240
it's that plus, all of the adenosine

01:00:16.240 --> 01:00:18.760
that's been building up during the time

01:00:18.760 --> 01:00:20.750
that the caffeine has been in my system.

01:00:20.750 --> 01:00:22.700
- So sort of an avalanche of adenosine.

01:00:22.700 --> 01:00:25.571
- It is a tsunami wave, yeah
and that's the caffeine crash.

01:00:25.571 --> 01:00:26.853
- And it's interesting
because the caffeine crash

01:00:26.853 --> 01:00:31.420
at two o'clock in the afternoon
when you have work to do

01:00:31.420 --> 01:00:32.350
is a terrible thing.

01:00:32.350 --> 01:00:34.960
But what about the person,

01:00:34.960 --> 01:00:37.220
maybe this person is me in my 20s,

01:00:37.220 --> 01:00:40.910
who says, I'm going to
drink caffeine all day long.

01:00:40.910 --> 01:00:42.560
And then I want the crash.

01:00:42.560 --> 01:00:45.890
Because at nine or 10pm,
if I stop drinking caffeine

01:00:45.890 --> 01:00:48.840
at say, 6pm, and I crash,

01:00:48.840 --> 01:00:53.290
then I crash into a slumber,
a deep night of sleep.

01:00:53.290 --> 01:00:55.700
Is that sleep really as
deep as I think it is?

01:00:55.700 --> 01:00:57.730
Because given the half life of caffeine

01:00:57.730 --> 01:01:00.490
that you mentioned a few moments ago,

01:01:00.490 --> 01:01:01.690
I have to imagine that

01:01:01.690 --> 01:01:04.080
having some of that caffeine
circulating in my system

01:01:04.080 --> 01:01:06.610
might disrupt the depth of sleep,

01:01:06.610 --> 01:01:09.260
or somehow the architecture
of sleep in a way

01:01:09.260 --> 01:01:11.945
that even if I get eight,

01:01:11.945 --> 01:01:13.490
or who knows even 10 hours of sleep,

01:01:13.490 --> 01:01:16.980
it might not be as restorative
as I would like it to be.

01:01:16.980 --> 01:01:19.120
- Yeah, and that is the danger,

01:01:19.120 --> 01:01:20.120
just sort of that, you know,

01:01:20.120 --> 01:01:22.250
those people that you described who say,

01:01:22.250 --> 01:01:24.840
and I, a lot of them
will speak with me too

01:01:24.840 --> 01:01:27.500
say, look, I can have
two espressos with dinner

01:01:27.500 --> 01:01:29.900
and I fall asleep fine and I stay asleep.

01:01:29.900 --> 01:01:32.270
Because usually those
are the two phenotypes

01:01:32.270 --> 01:01:34.510
that we typically see
with too much caffeine.

01:01:34.510 --> 01:01:37.120
I just can't fall asleep
as easily as I want to,

01:01:37.120 --> 01:01:39.540
or I fall asleep, but I
just can't stay asleep.

01:01:39.540 --> 01:01:42.220
And caffeine can do both of
those things quite potently.

01:01:42.220 --> 01:01:45.650
- How late in the day do you
think is assuming somebody,

01:01:45.650 --> 01:01:48.100
translate this folks, if you
go to bed earlier or later,

01:01:48.100 --> 01:01:49.750
you have to shift the hours accordingly.

01:01:49.750 --> 01:01:52.400
But given somebody who typically

01:01:52.400 --> 01:01:53.980
gets into bed around 10:00, 10:30,

01:01:53.980 --> 01:01:57.513
and falls asleep around 11:00, 11:30.

01:01:58.410 --> 01:02:02.690
When would you recommend
they halt caffeine intake?

01:02:02.690 --> 01:02:04.670
And these are not strict prescriptives,

01:02:04.670 --> 01:02:05.900
but I think people do benefit

01:02:05.900 --> 01:02:08.480
from having some fairly clear guidelines

01:02:08.480 --> 01:02:11.010
of what might work for them.

01:02:11.010 --> 01:02:15.080
Would you say cut off caffeine,
by what time of the day?

01:02:15.080 --> 01:02:16.110
- I would usually say

01:02:16.110 --> 01:02:17.860
take your typical bedtime

01:02:17.860 --> 01:02:21.760
and count back sort of somewhere
between 10 to eight hours

01:02:21.760 --> 01:02:23.390
is probably getting a little bit close.

01:02:23.390 --> 01:02:27.270
But take back sort of 10
hours or eight hours of time,

01:02:27.270 --> 01:02:30.460
that's the time when you
should really stop, you know,

01:02:30.460 --> 01:02:33.130
using caffeine is the suggestion.

01:02:33.130 --> 01:02:34.830
And the reason is because for those people

01:02:34.830 --> 01:02:37.490
who even just keep
drinking up until you know,

01:02:37.490 --> 01:02:40.160
into the evening, you're right,

01:02:40.160 --> 01:02:41.570
that they can fall asleep fine,

01:02:41.570 --> 01:02:42.610
maybe they stay asleep,

01:02:42.610 --> 01:02:46.680
but the depth of their deep
sleep is not as deep anymore.

01:02:46.680 --> 01:02:49.040
And so there are two consequences.

01:02:49.040 --> 01:02:50.460
The first is that for me,

01:02:50.460 --> 01:02:53.200
and it can be up to by 30%,

01:02:53.200 --> 01:02:55.730
and for me to drop your deep sleep by 30%,

01:02:55.730 --> 01:02:59.480
I'd have to age you by
between 10 to 12 years,

01:02:59.480 --> 01:03:01.450
or you can just do it
every night to yourself

01:03:01.450 --> 01:03:03.600
with a couple of espressos.

01:03:03.600 --> 01:03:07.510
The second is that you then
wake up the next morning,

01:03:07.510 --> 01:03:10.447
and you think, well, I didn't
have problems falling asleep

01:03:10.447 --> 01:03:13.400
and I didn't have problems staying asleep,

01:03:13.400 --> 01:03:15.900
but I don't feel particularly
restored by my sleep.

01:03:15.900 --> 01:03:18.730
So now I'm reaching for
three or four cups of coffee

01:03:18.730 --> 01:03:20.212
the next morning,

01:03:20.212 --> 01:03:21.620
rather than just two or
three cups of coffee.

01:03:21.620 --> 01:03:23.957
And so goes this dependency cycle,

01:03:23.957 --> 01:03:26.310
that you then need your uppers

01:03:26.310 --> 01:03:28.050
to wake you up in the morning,

01:03:28.050 --> 01:03:31.100
And then sometimes people will
use alcohol in the evening

01:03:31.100 --> 01:03:34.360
to bring them down because
they're overly caffeinated

01:03:34.360 --> 01:03:36.220
and alcohol, and we can
speak about that, too,

01:03:36.220 --> 01:03:39.800
also has very deleterious
impacts on your sleep as well.

01:03:39.800 --> 01:03:44.040
So you're right that it's
not just the quantity

01:03:44.040 --> 01:03:46.390
of your sleep, or even
difficulties falling

01:03:46.390 --> 01:03:47.858
