01:25:16.370 --> 01:25:20.610
And certainly it's in widespread use.

01:25:20.610 --> 01:25:22.210
Certainly not recommending people do it.

01:25:22.210 --> 01:25:24.460
I have my own thoughts
about marijuana CBD.

01:25:24.460 --> 01:25:26.510
I've been fortunate, I suppose

01:25:26.510 --> 01:25:29.430
that I don't particularly
like marijuana or CBD.

01:25:29.430 --> 01:25:31.763
I don't even know if I've ever tried CBD.

01:25:32.750 --> 01:25:37.750
First of all, does marijuana
disrupt the depth of sleep,

01:25:37.970 --> 01:25:40.200
the architecture of sleep?

01:25:40.200 --> 01:25:44.090
And if so, as with alcohol and caffeine

01:25:44.090 --> 01:25:47.110
does when you ingest it

01:25:47.110 --> 01:25:49.380
or when it's in your bloodstream does,

01:25:49.380 --> 01:25:50.780
relative to when you go to sleep,

01:25:50.780 --> 01:25:52.310
does that play an important role?

01:25:52.310 --> 01:25:55.290
So does marijuana disrupt sleep?

01:25:55.290 --> 01:25:56.880
- Yeah, it does.

01:25:56.880 --> 01:26:00.410
And there's a pretty
good amount of data on

01:26:00.410 --> 01:26:03.730
so we can break sort of cannabis down into

01:26:03.730 --> 01:26:05.660
two of its key ingredients.

01:26:05.660 --> 01:26:10.510
We've got THC tetrahydrocannabinol,
and we've got CBD

01:26:10.510 --> 01:26:14.630
and CBD is sort of the less psychotic

01:26:14.630 --> 01:26:17.680
what we think of as the non
psychoactive components.

01:26:17.680 --> 01:26:21.160
In other words, when you
take CBD, you don't get high.

01:26:21.160 --> 01:26:24.190
If you take THC, you can get high.

01:26:24.190 --> 01:26:27.060
That's the psychoactive
part of the equation.

01:26:27.060 --> 01:26:29.812
- Are both considered sedatives
in the technical sense?

01:26:29.812 --> 01:26:32.740
- No, they're not.

01:26:32.740 --> 01:26:36.950
Neither of them have that class right now.

01:26:36.950 --> 01:26:41.950
THC can, seems to speed up the time

01:26:42.350 --> 01:26:44.320
with which you fall asleep.

01:26:44.320 --> 01:26:48.200
But again, if you look at the
electrical brainwave signature

01:26:48.200 --> 01:26:51.600
of you're falling asleep
with and without that THC,

01:26:51.600 --> 01:26:54.050
it's not going to be an ideal fit.

01:26:54.050 --> 01:26:56.510
So you could argue it's non natural,

01:26:56.510 --> 01:26:58.970
but many people use THC for that fact,

01:26:58.970 --> 01:27:01.640
because they find it
difficult to fall asleep.

01:27:01.640 --> 01:27:04.070
And it can speed the onset

01:27:04.070 --> 01:27:05.490
of at least non consciousness,

01:27:05.490 --> 01:27:07.570
I guess is the best way of describing it.

01:27:07.570 --> 01:27:10.370
But there are problems with THC.

01:27:10.370 --> 01:27:11.910
And they are twofold.

01:27:11.910 --> 01:27:13.390
The first is that it too,

01:27:13.390 --> 01:27:16.960
but through different mechanisms
seems to block REM sleep.

01:27:16.960 --> 01:27:18.950
And that's why a lot of
people when they're using

01:27:18.950 --> 01:27:20.794
will tell me look, you know,

01:27:20.794 --> 01:27:22.410
I definitely, I was dreaming.

01:27:22.410 --> 01:27:24.710
Or I don't remember, you
know many of my dreams.

01:27:24.710 --> 01:27:28.140
And then when they stop using THC,

01:27:28.140 --> 01:27:31.900
let's say I was having, you
know, just crazy, crazy dreams

01:27:31.900 --> 01:27:35.390
and the reason is because
there is a rebound mechanism.

01:27:35.390 --> 01:27:36.850
REM sleep is very clever.

01:27:36.850 --> 01:27:39.120
And alcohol is the same way in this sense,

01:27:39.120 --> 01:27:41.030
it's the same homeostatic mechanism.

01:27:41.030 --> 01:27:42.160
Some people will tell me,

01:27:42.160 --> 01:27:44.660
look, if I have a bit
of a wild Friday night

01:27:44.660 --> 01:27:46.490
with some alcohol, you know,

01:27:46.490 --> 01:27:48.820
maybe I'll sleep late
into the next morning.

01:27:48.820 --> 01:27:52.150
And I'll just have these
really intense dreams.

01:27:52.150 --> 01:27:54.730
So and I thought I wasn't
having any REM sleep,

01:27:54.730 --> 01:27:56.360
well, the way it works is that

01:27:56.360 --> 01:27:59.090
it's during in the middle
of the night, really,

01:27:59.090 --> 01:28:01.938
when alcohol blocks your REM sleep.

01:28:01.938 --> 01:28:03.930
And your brain is smart

01:28:03.930 --> 01:28:06.930
it understands how much REM
sleep you should have had,

01:28:06.930 --> 01:28:08.680
how much REM sleep you have not

01:28:08.680 --> 01:28:10.700
because the alcohol
has been in the system.

01:28:10.700 --> 01:28:12.810
And finally, in those early morning hours,

01:28:12.810 --> 01:28:14.716
when you're getting through
to sort of, you know,

01:28:14.716 --> 01:28:15.715
[cross talking]

01:28:15.715 --> 01:28:16.930
six, seven, 8:00am all of a sudden,

01:28:16.930 --> 01:28:18.500
your brain not only goes back

01:28:18.500 --> 01:28:21.270
to having the same amount
of REM it would have had,

01:28:21.270 --> 01:28:23.900
it does that plus it tries to get back

01:28:23.900 --> 01:28:25.790
all of the REM sleep that it's lost.

01:28:25.790 --> 01:28:27.610
Does it get back all of the REM sleep?

01:28:27.610 --> 01:28:28.550
No, it doesn't.

01:28:28.550 --> 01:28:31.750
It never gets back all of
the REM sleep, but it tries.

01:28:31.750 --> 01:28:34.780
And so you have these really
intense periods of REM sleep.

01:28:34.780 --> 01:28:37.950
Hence you have really
intense bizarre dreams.

01:28:37.950 --> 01:28:40.580
And that's what happens also with THC,

01:28:40.580 --> 01:28:44.060
you build up this pressure for REM sleep,

01:28:44.060 --> 01:28:45.793
this debt for REM sleep,

01:28:45.793 --> 01:28:47.691
will you ever pay it back?

01:28:47.691 --> 01:28:49.670
Doesn't seem as though you get back

01:28:49.670 --> 01:28:51.310
everything that you lost,

01:28:51.310 --> 01:28:52.850
but will you get back some of it?

01:28:52.850 --> 01:28:55.280
Yes, the brain will start to devour more

01:28:55.280 --> 01:28:59.074
because it's been starved
of REM sleep for so long.

01:28:59.074 --> 01:29:02.260
But one of the bigger problems with THC

01:29:02.260 --> 01:29:05.870
that we worry about is
withdrawal dependency.

01:29:05.870 --> 01:29:09.190
So as you start to use THC for sleep,

01:29:09.190 --> 01:29:12.920
there can be a dependency tolerance.

01:29:12.920 --> 01:29:16.820
So you start to need more to
get the same sleep benefit.

01:29:16.820 --> 01:29:18.330
And when you stop using,

01:29:18.330 --> 01:29:21.780
you usually get a very
severe rebound insomnia.

01:29:21.780 --> 01:29:23.340
And in fact, it's so potent

01:29:23.340 --> 01:29:25.893
that it's typically part of the clinical

01:29:25.893 --> 01:29:30.660
withdrawal profile from THC from cannabis.

01:29:30.660 --> 01:29:32.692
- And there's anxiety withdrawal.

01:29:32.692 --> 01:29:37.692
I you know, I don't ask anybody
to change their behavior,

01:29:38.410 --> 01:29:40.590
we just as you said, we
