01:45:46.700 --> 01:45:48.850
is not because it helps in
the generation of sleep,

01:45:48.850 --> 01:45:50.220
we know that it doesn't,

01:45:50.220 --> 01:45:54.450
it's because it too seems to
drop core body temperature.

01:45:54.450 --> 01:45:55.780
- There it is, temperature again.

01:45:55.780 --> 01:45:57.160
I'm fascinated these days,

01:45:57.160 --> 01:45:59.050
more and more by temperature,

01:45:59.050 --> 01:46:03.660
as maybe not just a
reflection of brain state

01:46:03.660 --> 01:46:05.500
and wakefulness and in sleep,

01:46:05.500 --> 01:46:08.580
but actually a lever
that is quite powerful.

01:46:08.580 --> 01:46:10.120
- I think it's both.

01:46:10.120 --> 01:46:11.590
- And with all the interest
in ice baths and hot showers

01:46:11.590 --> 01:46:12.600
and saunas and stuff,

01:46:12.600 --> 01:46:15.060
something that we will
definitely touch on.

01:46:15.060 --> 01:46:17.360
Temperature variation is so key.

01:46:17.360 --> 01:46:20.230
So if melatonin is
dropping body temperature

01:46:20.230 --> 01:46:22.620
by a degree or so something
that you've said before

01:46:22.620 --> 01:46:25.440
can help induce a sleepy state.

01:46:25.440 --> 01:46:28.080
Maybe that's what's allowing
people to get in to sleep.

01:46:28.080 --> 01:46:29.439
- I think that's one possibility.

01:46:29.439 --> 01:46:30.530
I don't think melatonin by itself

01:46:30.530 --> 01:46:33.210
will drop it by it sort
of, you know, a degree,

01:46:33.210 --> 01:46:34.760
certainly not a degree Celsius.

01:46:34.760 --> 01:46:37.280
And for order in us to fall asleep,

01:46:37.280 --> 01:46:38.930
and then stay asleep across the night,

01:46:38.930 --> 01:46:41.070
we do need to drop our
core body temperature

01:46:41.070 --> 01:46:42.860
by about one degree Celsius,

01:46:42.860 --> 01:46:46.000
or about two to three degrees Fahrenheit.

01:46:46.000 --> 01:46:47.500
And that's why it's always easier

01:46:47.500 --> 01:46:50.200
to fall asleep in a room
that's too cold than too hot.

01:46:51.420 --> 01:46:54.490
I think that that's one potential avenue

01:46:54.490 --> 01:46:58.120
that we are considering
thinking more deeply about

01:46:58.120 --> 01:47:00.210
when it comes to melatonin.

01:47:00.210 --> 01:47:03.590
And then the other is
melatonin as an antioxidant.

01:47:03.590 --> 01:47:05.890
But let me table that for now.

01:47:05.890 --> 01:47:07.820
'Cause I'll just get us sidetracked.

01:47:07.820 --> 01:47:11.580
That's what we know so far about melatonin

01:47:11.580 --> 01:47:15.460
in terms of its supplementation
benefit or lack thereof.

01:47:15.460 --> 01:47:17.720
Two final points that I shouldn't forget,

01:47:17.720 --> 01:47:21.030
one is the only population
where we typically see

01:47:21.030 --> 01:47:23.630
some benefit, and it often is prescribed

01:47:23.630 --> 01:47:25.970
is in older adults, because as we.

01:47:25.970 --> 01:47:27.870
- Older meaning 60 and older?

01:47:27.870 --> 01:47:29.710
- Yeah, 60, 65 and older

01:47:29.710 --> 01:47:31.150
because as we get older,

01:47:31.150 --> 01:47:32.990
you can typically have what's called

01:47:32.990 --> 01:47:35.140
calcification of the pineal gland.

01:47:35.140 --> 01:47:37.800
Which means that that gland
that's releasing melatonin

01:47:37.800 --> 01:47:39.662
doesn't work as well anymore.

01:47:39.662 --> 01:47:44.662
As a consequence, they tend to
have a flatter overall curve

01:47:44.760 --> 01:47:47.070
of melatonin release throughout the night.

01:47:47.070 --> 01:47:49.320
It's not this beautiful, lovely peak,

01:47:49.320 --> 01:47:52.050
and this bullhorn message of its darkness,

01:47:52.050 --> 01:47:53.390
please get to sleep.

01:47:53.390 --> 01:47:55.940
That's why older adults can
have problems falling asleep

01:47:55.940 --> 01:47:57.000
or staying asleep.

01:47:57.000 --> 01:48:00.400
It's not the only reason by
any stretch of the imagination.

01:48:00.400 --> 01:48:01.570
But it's one of the reasons

01:48:01.570 --> 01:48:04.670
and it's why melatonin
supplementation in those cohorts,

01:48:04.670 --> 01:48:07.890
older adults, and especially
older adults with insomnia,

01:48:07.890 --> 01:48:09.720
people have thought about that

01:48:09.720 --> 01:48:12.570
as maybe an appropriate use case.

01:48:12.570 --> 01:48:14.010
- Well, along those lines,

01:48:14.010 --> 01:48:17.597
if we were to compare dosages, I don't,

01:48:17.597 --> 01:48:19.310
do we know how much melatonin

01:48:19.310 --> 01:48:22.717
is typically released into
the bloodstream per night?

01:48:22.717 --> 01:48:26.480
And can we use that as a
kind of a rule of thumb

01:48:26.480 --> 01:48:28.180
by which to compare the typical amount

01:48:28.180 --> 01:48:29.680
that someone would supplement?

01:48:29.680 --> 01:48:32.035
Typically, the supplements
for melatonin that I see

01:48:32.035 --> 01:48:35.140
in the pharmacy and elsewhere online

01:48:35.140 --> 01:48:38.250
range anywhere from one milligram to 12,

01:48:38.250 --> 01:48:40.410
or even 20 milligrams.

01:48:40.410 --> 01:48:45.040
My guess is that a normal
night's release of melatonin

01:48:45.040 --> 01:48:47.880
typical for somebody
in their 20s, 30s, 40s

01:48:47.880 --> 01:48:51.142
would be far lower than
that, am I correct or wrong?

01:48:51.142 --> 01:48:54.100
- Yeah, it's many magnitudes lower.

01:48:54.100 --> 01:48:56.520
And this is one of the problems
is that I see that too.

01:48:56.520 --> 01:48:59.590
I see, you know, typical
doses are, you know,

01:48:59.590 --> 01:49:01.460
five milligrams or 10 milligrams

01:49:01.460 --> 01:49:04.360
and of course, you know, if
you're a supplement company,

01:49:04.360 --> 01:49:06.770
you know, putting 10 milligrams
versus five milligrams,

01:49:06.770 --> 01:49:08.010
if that's what you're actually doing,

01:49:08.010 --> 01:49:09.960
which we'll speak about purity as well.

01:49:11.120 --> 01:49:14.840
You know, it's kind of
like the super gulp size,

01:49:14.840 --> 01:49:17.050
nobody wants to lower price,

01:49:17.050 --> 01:49:19.170
they just want you to you know,

01:49:19.170 --> 01:49:20.980
we'll just give you
more for the same price.

01:49:20.980 --> 01:49:22.050
And that's how we'll compete.

01:49:22.050 --> 01:49:25.120
So it's been this escalating arms race

01:49:25.120 --> 01:49:27.030
of melatonin concentration,

01:49:27.030 --> 01:49:29.820
and it really does not look meaningful

01:49:29.820 --> 01:49:33.040
for, you know, for sleep in any way.

01:49:33.040 --> 01:49:34.500
What we've actually found

01:49:34.500 --> 01:49:36.650
is that the optimal doses

01:49:36.650 --> 01:49:38.760
for where you do get sleep benefits

01:49:38.760 --> 01:49:41.167
in the populations that we've looked at,

01:49:41.167 --> 01:49:46.167
are somewhere between 0.1 and
0.3 milligrams of melatonin.

01:49:47.260 --> 01:49:50.680
In other words, the
typical doses are usually

01:49:50.680 --> 01:49:53.480
10 times, 20 times maybe more

01:49:53.480 --> 01:49:56.550
than what your body
would naturally expect.

01:49:56.550 --> 01:50:00.530
And this is what we call a
supra physiological dose.

01:50:00.530 --> 01:50:02.370
In other words, it's far above

01:50:02.370 --> 01:50:04.900
what is physiologically normal?

01:50:04.900 --> 01:50:06.290
You know, and to put that in context,

01:50:06.290 --> 01:50:07.530
imagine I said to you,

01:50:07.530 --> 01:50:11.250
I want you to eat 20
times as much food today.

01:50:11.250 --> 01:50:13.620
- I thought you're going to
use testosterone as example.

01:50:13.620 --> 01:50:14.903
You're going to take 300 times

01:50:14.903 --> 01:50:16.810
the normal amount of testosterone

01:50:16.810 --> 01:50:20.460
we know that would have
tons of deleterious effects

01:50:20.460 --> 01:50:21.450
it would be terrible.

01:50:21.450 --> 01:50:22.710
And yet you can do this.

01:50:22.710 --> 01:50:24.270
One thing that I'm concerned about

01:50:24.270 --> 01:50:26.965
about these super physiological
levels of melatonin

01:50:26.965 --> 01:50:29.550
is that many years ago,
actually, here at Berkeley,

01:50:29.550 --> 01:50:30.480
when I was a graduate student,

01:50:30.480 --> 01:50:33.390
we would inject animals

01:50:33.390 --> 01:50:36.800
which were seasonally breeding
animals with melatonin.

01:50:36.800 --> 01:50:41.310
And the consequence of
that was that their gonads,

01:50:41.310 --> 01:50:43.700
either their testes or
ovaries would shrink,

01:50:43.700 --> 01:50:46.700
many hundred fold or more.

01:50:46.700 --> 01:50:48.910
In other words, they would go from having

01:50:48.910 --> 01:50:51.450
nice healthy sized hamster testicles,

01:50:51.450 --> 01:50:54.360
what a hamster would consider
healthy size for a hamster

01:50:54.360 --> 01:50:56.470
and they would shrink to
the size of a grain of rice.

01:50:56.470 --> 01:50:59.360
So from like an almonds to a
grain size of a grain of rice.

01:50:59.360 --> 01:51:00.730
I had to see that only once

01:51:00.730 --> 01:51:02.370
for me to be very concerned about

01:51:02.370 --> 01:51:04.460
super physiological levels of melatonin.

01:51:04.460 --> 01:51:06.790
And I realized that melatonin
does different things

01:51:06.790 --> 01:51:08.341
in different species.

01:51:08.341 --> 01:51:10.960
We are not hamsters, we
are not seasonal breeders

01:51:10.960 --> 01:51:12.460
seasonally restricted breeders,

01:51:12.460 --> 01:51:14.967
there might be more breeding
during certain seasons,

01:51:14.967 --> 01:51:15.800
I don't know those data.

01:51:15.800 --> 01:51:19.230
But nonetheless, hormones are powerful.

01:51:19.230 --> 01:51:22.020
And sure there is an optimal,

01:51:22.020 --> 01:51:25.440
and sometimes we see that going

01:51:25.440 --> 01:51:28.330
slightly above endogenous
levels for certain hormones

01:51:28.330 --> 01:51:30.500
not always, can have beneficial effects.

01:51:30.500 --> 01:51:33.040
And sometimes it can
have detrimental effects.

01:51:33.040 --> 01:51:35.840
I'm just concerned
about taking high levels

01:51:35.840 --> 01:51:40.100
of a hormone that has effects
on the reproductive axis

01:51:40.100 --> 01:51:42.860
and that's one of the reasons
why I get very concerned

01:51:42.860 --> 01:51:46.090
when I see people really
getting aggressive

01:51:46.090 --> 01:51:49.190
about melatonin supplementation

01:51:49.190 --> 01:51:53.310
taking 100, 10, 500,
sometimes even 10,000 times

01:51:53.310 --> 01:51:54.970
the amount that we would normally release.

01:51:54.970 --> 01:51:55.890
That's my concern,

01:51:55.890 --> 01:51:58.830
although it's not nested in
any one specific human study.

01:51:58.830 --> 01:52:00.914
I just don't like to see,

01:52:00.914 --> 01:52:02.707
I certainly don't want to see other people

01:52:02.707 --> 01:52:06.220
and I don't want to
personally take a hormone

01:52:06.220 --> 01:52:10.670
that's known to be androgen
suppressive at high levels.

01:52:10.670 --> 01:52:12.640
Why would I take that?

01:52:12.640 --> 01:52:14.360
That's the question I ask myself.

01:52:14.360 --> 01:52:16.360
- I think it's a very,
you know, good point.

01:52:16.360 --> 01:52:21.137
And if you look at some of
the evidence around, you know,

01:52:21.137 --> 01:52:24.840
melatonins lethality if you
want to go to that extreme,

01:52:24.840 --> 01:52:27.560
for the most part, you
know, it's pretty safe.

01:52:27.560 --> 01:52:29.690
- You mean, you can take a
lot of it before you die?

01:52:29.690 --> 01:52:30.970
- Right, exactly yeah.

01:52:30.970 --> 01:52:33.258
- But I don't know that
that's the criteria.

01:52:33.258 --> 01:52:34.100
- That should be your yardstick for,

01:52:34.100 --> 01:52:36.956
because, you know, you
really need to think about

01:52:36.956 --> 01:52:38.555
your, you know, your health,

01:52:38.555 --> 01:52:40.300
not just whether this thing
is going to kill you or not

01:52:40.300 --> 01:52:44.633
as the decision matrix
through which you pop a pill.

01:52:45.520 --> 01:52:49.100
And it comes on to this
concern around melatonin

01:52:49.100 --> 01:52:50.600
because there was a study,

01:52:50.600 --> 01:52:53.320
I think it's one that you mentioned too

01:52:53.320 --> 01:52:54.900
where they looked at over,

01:52:54.900 --> 01:52:57.520
I think it was at least
over 20 different brands

01:52:57.520 --> 01:52:59.700
of melatonin supplements.

01:52:59.700 --> 01:53:01.950
And what they found is
that based on what it said,

01:53:01.950 --> 01:53:05.000
on the bottle versus what was
in the capsules themselves,

01:53:05.000 --> 01:53:08.490
it ranged from, I think it was 83% less

01:53:08.490 --> 01:53:09.870
than what it said on the bottle

01:53:09.870 --> 01:53:14.310
to 478% more than what
it said on the bottle.

01:53:14.310 --> 01:53:18.870
Now, if that's a 10
milligram, you know, pill,

01:53:18.870 --> 01:53:23.870
and it's 478% more than 10 milligrams,

01:53:23.980 --> 01:53:26.330
and we're already at 10 milligrams

01:53:26.330 --> 01:53:28.790
at many tens of times more

01:53:28.790 --> 01:53:31.160
than is a physiological rather than

01:53:31.160 --> 01:53:34.120
a supra physiological dose,

01:53:34.120 --> 01:53:35.990
we do need to be a bit thoughtful.

01:53:35.990 --> 01:53:38.003
- Yeah, remember those hamsters folks.

01:53:39.570 --> 01:53:41.900
Well, and I do appreciate

01:53:41.900 --> 01:53:43.250
the deep dive on melatonin

01:53:43.250 --> 01:53:46.330
because I think people need to understand

01:53:46.330 --> 01:53:48.610
that it's nuanced, it's
a matter of dosages,

01:53:48.610 --> 01:53:50.050
and timing, etcetera.

01:53:50.050 --> 01:53:51.220
And then it may have its place

01:53:51.220 --> 01:53:53.050
as you mentioned in older individuals.

01:53:53.050 --> 01:53:56.770
And I should mention
that I'm an avid consumer

01:53:56.770 --> 01:53:59.600
of supplements that I believe in for me

01:53:59.600 --> 01:54:00.940
and I have been for a very long time.

01:54:00.940 --> 01:54:04.370
So I'm by no means anti supplement.

01:54:04.370 --> 01:54:07.220
Some supplements I refuse
to take or avoid taking

01:54:07.220 --> 01:54:12.068
others I quite avidly take
and along those lines,

01:54:12.068 --> 01:54:15.628
I personally and I don't know

01:54:15.628 --> 01:54:17.640
what your thoughts on this are.

01:54:17.640 --> 01:54:19.170
But there are a few things

01:54:19.170 --> 01:54:20.540
that I've personally found beneficial.

01:54:20.540 --> 01:54:21.630
I love your thoughts on them.

01:54:21.630 --> 01:54:24.280
And I would love it if
you would tell me that

01:54:24.280 --> 01:54:26.610
everything I'm about
to refer to is placebo,

01:54:26.610 --> 01:54:28.310
that would be fine.

01:54:28.310 --> 01:54:29.143
So that's what we do,

01:54:29.143 --> 01:54:29.976
we're scientists we argue

01:54:29.976 --> 01:54:34.540
and then we remain friends
in as it goes away.

01:54:34.540 --> 01:54:38.350
So magnesium, there are
many forms of magnesium.

01:54:38.350 --> 01:54:40.110
Magnesium citrate is a as we know,

01:54:40.110 --> 01:54:41.880
is a terrific laxative.

01:54:41.880 --> 01:54:45.640
Magnesium malate seems, at
least from a few studies

01:54:45.640 --> 01:54:48.200
seems to relieve some of
delayed onset muscle soreness

01:54:48.200 --> 01:54:50.000
doesn't seem to create a kind of sedation.

01:54:50.000 --> 01:54:51.150
Two forms of magnesium

01:54:51.150 --> 01:54:53.440
that I'm aware of magnesium biglycinate

01:54:53.440 --> 01:54:54.903
and magnesium threonate.

01:54:55.893 --> 01:55:00.490
We believe based on the
data can more actively cross

01:55:00.490 --> 01:55:01.580
the blood brain barrier.

01:55:01.580 --> 01:55:02.500
So you put in your gut,

01:55:02.500 --> 01:55:03.910
but some of that needs
to go into your brain

01:55:03.910 --> 01:55:05.630
in order to have the sedative effect.

01:55:05.630 --> 01:55:08.170
What are your thoughts on
magnesium supplementation?

01:55:08.170 --> 01:55:10.610
Do you supplement with magnesium?

01:55:10.610 --> 01:55:14.580
And what studies would
you like to see done

01:55:14.580 --> 01:55:16.220
if they haven't been done already.

01:55:16.220 --> 01:55:18.964
- So I don't supplement with magnesium.

01:55:18.964 --> 01:55:21.840
But I do think threonate is interesting

01:55:21.840 --> 01:55:24.510
because of that higher capacity

01:55:24.510 --> 01:55:27.002
to cross the blood brain barrier

01:55:27.002 --> 01:55:28.560
and actually have a central
nervous system effect.

01:55:28.560 --> 01:55:30.200
And the reason that that interests me

01:55:30.200 --> 01:55:33.910
is because the sleep is
by the brain of the brain,

01:55:33.910 --> 01:55:37.890
and also for the brain,
as well as for the body.

01:55:37.890 --> 01:55:40.870
We just don't have a
particularly good set of studies

01:55:40.870 --> 01:55:43.840
that have targeted exclusively threonate.

01:55:43.840 --> 01:55:45.140
We do have lots of studies

01:55:45.140 --> 01:55:48.290
that have just looked at
magnesium in general for sleep.

01:55:48.290 --> 01:55:51.613
And overall, the data is uncompelling.

01:55:52.515 --> 01:55:54.323
- Interesting.
- And for a while,

01:55:55.430 --> 01:55:57.453
I was confused as to why,

01:55:58.355 --> 01:56:01.940
where did this come from this
kind of myth of magnesium?

01:56:01.940 --> 01:56:04.380
So I started looking
back into the literature

01:56:04.380 --> 01:56:08.930
and I've best traced it at
least as far as I can tell,

01:56:08.930 --> 01:56:10.730
to early studies showing that

01:56:10.730 --> 01:56:13.830
those who are deficient in magnesium

01:56:13.830 --> 01:56:15.830
also had sleep problems.

01:56:15.830 --> 01:56:17.950
They had other problems too, of course,

01:56:17.950 --> 01:56:21.260
but sleep problems were
one of that set of sequelae

01:56:21.260 --> 01:56:24.300
that came from having lower magnesium.

01:56:24.300 --> 01:56:28.160
And when they supplemented with magnesium

01:56:28.160 --> 01:56:29.810
and tried to restore those levels,

01:56:29.810 --> 01:56:32.370
some of those sleep problems dissipated.

01:56:32.370 --> 01:56:35.050
And then that seems to have gotten lost

01:56:35.050 --> 01:56:37.100
in sort of some game of sort of like

01:56:37.100 --> 01:56:38.500
whispers around the room

01:56:38.500 --> 01:56:40.500
and it's become translated into

01:56:40.500 --> 01:56:42.770
people who don't have sleep problems,

01:56:42.770 --> 01:56:45.410
who are healthy sleepers, and
who are healthy in general,

01:56:45.410 --> 01:56:47.960
and who have healthy
normal levels of magnesium,

01:56:47.960 --> 01:56:51.650
if they take more magnesium,
they will sleep better.

01:56:51.650 --> 01:56:53.780
And the data really, there is not good.

01:56:53.780 --> 01:56:57.020
Once again, the only study that I've seen

01:56:57.020 --> 01:56:59.280
where magnesium did have some efficacy

01:56:59.280 --> 01:57:00.920
was in a study with older adults,

01:57:00.920 --> 01:57:03.050
I think they were 60 to 80 years old,

01:57:03.050 --> 01:57:05.120
it may have been exclusively women,

01:57:05.120 --> 01:57:06.540
now I think about it

01:57:06.540 --> 01:57:08.420
and they also had insomnia.

01:57:08.420 --> 01:57:11.730
And in that population,
you did see some benefits.

01:57:11.730 --> 01:57:13.330
And my guess is that

01:57:13.330 --> 01:57:15.770
because it's an older community as well,

01:57:15.770 --> 01:57:18.480
they were probably deficient in magnesium.

01:57:18.480 --> 01:57:20.550
So they fit the former category

01:57:20.550 --> 01:57:23.890
of simply when you're
deficient, and you restore,

01:57:23.890 --> 01:57:27.500
you can help sleep sort
of return to normal.

01:57:27.500 --> 01:57:30.277
But if you are not deficient
and you're healthy,

01:57:30.277 --> 01:57:31.500
and you're not old and
you don't have insomnia,

01:57:31.500 --> 01:57:33.300
and you're supplementing

01:57:33.300 --> 01:57:35.730
thinking that it provides
sleep, right now,

01:57:35.730 --> 01:57:37.660
the data isn't supportive of that.

