02:20:50.180 --> 02:20:51.150
- That's right, yep.

02:20:51.150 --> 02:20:53.370
Now, it's not that I am immune

02:20:53.370 --> 02:20:56.560
to what we call the
postprandial dip in alertness.

02:20:56.560 --> 02:20:57.830
I definitely feel as though

02:20:57.830 --> 02:21:01.250
there can be this kind of afternoon lull,

02:21:01.250 --> 02:21:04.650
where, you know, I'm
not quite as on as I was

02:21:04.650 --> 02:21:06.160
at 11 o'clock in the morning.

02:21:06.160 --> 02:21:07.940
And we know the physiology to that,

02:21:07.940 --> 02:21:10.763
which brings us back to whether
we were designed to nap.

02:21:11.960 --> 02:21:15.180
So for naps, we've done
lots of different studies

02:21:15.180 --> 02:21:17.230
and other colleagues have
done these studies too.

02:21:17.230 --> 02:21:19.610
Naps can have some really great benefits,

02:21:19.610 --> 02:21:22.230
we found benefits for
cardiovascular health,

02:21:22.230 --> 02:21:23.760
blood pressure, for example,

02:21:23.760 --> 02:21:26.070
we found benefits for levels of cortisol,

02:21:26.070 --> 02:21:28.410
we found benefits for learning and memory,

02:21:28.410 --> 02:21:30.940
and also emotional regulation.

02:21:30.940 --> 02:21:33.490
- How long are the naps,
typically, in those studies?

02:21:33.490 --> 02:21:36.280
- Anywhere between 20
minutes to 90 minutes.

02:21:36.280 --> 02:21:38.730
Sometimes we like to
use a 90 minute window

02:21:38.730 --> 02:21:42.060
so that the participant can
have a full cycle of sleep,

02:21:42.060 --> 02:21:44.600
and therefore they get
both non REM and REM sleep

02:21:44.600 --> 02:21:45.740
within that time period.

02:21:45.740 --> 02:21:47.200
Then when we wake them up,

02:21:47.200 --> 02:21:48.890
we usually wait a period of time

02:21:48.890 --> 02:21:51.250
to get them past what
we call sleep inertia,

02:21:51.250 --> 02:21:53.110
which is that kind of window of grogginess

02:21:53.110 --> 02:21:55.810
where you say to you,
better half look, you know,

02:21:55.810 --> 02:21:57.400
darling, please don't

02:21:57.400 --> 02:21:59.100
speak to me for the first hour after I've.

02:21:59.100 --> 02:22:00.270
- Don't anything right now.

02:22:00.270 --> 02:22:02.040
- After the first hour
of waking up, you know,

02:22:02.040 --> 02:22:04.768
I'm not just, I'm just not
the best version of myself.

02:22:04.768 --> 02:22:06.780
So we wait for that time period,

02:22:06.780 --> 02:22:08.520
and then we do some testing.

02:22:08.520 --> 02:22:10.240
And we've done some
testing before and after,

02:22:10.240 --> 02:22:11.400
and we look at the change.

02:22:11.400 --> 02:22:13.557
And that's how we measure
what was the benefit of naps

02:22:13.557 --> 02:22:15.850
and the reason why we
sometimes do 90 minutes

02:22:15.850 --> 02:22:17.840
so that they get all of
those stages of sleep.

02:22:17.840 --> 02:22:19.370
And then we correlate,

02:22:19.370 --> 02:22:22.230
how much benefit did you get from the nap,

02:22:22.230 --> 02:22:25.040
and how much of that
benefit was explained by

02:22:25.040 --> 02:22:27.700
what REM sleep you got,
what deep sleep you got,

02:22:27.700 --> 02:22:29.130
what light sleep you got?

02:22:29.130 --> 02:22:30.910
So that's the only reason that we use that

02:22:30.910 --> 02:22:32.834
as an experimental tool.

02:22:32.834 --> 02:22:34.840
What we've also found is that

02:22:34.840 --> 02:22:37.810
naps of as little as 17 minutes

02:22:37.810 --> 02:22:41.820
can have some quite potent
effects on for example, learning.

02:22:41.820 --> 02:22:43.540
None of this is novel,

02:22:43.540 --> 02:22:47.050
NASA pioneered this back in the 1990s.

02:22:47.050 --> 02:22:48.430
And during the missions,

02:22:48.430 --> 02:22:51.300
they were experimenting with
naps for their astronauts.

02:22:51.300 --> 02:22:55.510
And what they found was that
naps of little as 26 minutes,

02:22:55.510 --> 02:23:00.510
improved mission performance by 34%,

02:23:00.660 --> 02:23:04.460
and improved daytime alertness by 50%.

02:23:04.460 --> 02:23:06.850
And it birthed what was then called

02:23:06.850 --> 02:23:08.810
the NASA nap culture

02:23:08.810 --> 02:23:12.530
throughout all terrestrial NASA staff

02:23:12.530 --> 02:23:13.730
during that time period.

02:23:13.730 --> 02:23:17.020
So it's long been known that
naps can have a benefit.

02:23:17.020 --> 02:23:19.290
Naps, however, can have
a double edged sword

02:23:19.290 --> 02:23:22.140
there is a dark side to naps.

02:23:22.140 --> 02:23:24.760
And it comes back to
our story of adenosine

02:23:24.760 --> 02:23:26.100
and sleep pressure.

02:23:26.100 --> 02:23:27.250
The longer we're awake,

02:23:27.250 --> 02:23:30.020
the more of that sleep pressure
adenosine that we build up.

02:23:30.020 --> 02:23:32.770
But what I didn't tell
you is that when we sleep,

02:23:32.770 --> 02:23:34.480
the brain gets the chance

02:23:34.480 --> 02:23:38.640
to essentially clear out that adenosine.

02:23:38.640 --> 02:23:41.570
And after about 16 hours of wakefulness,

02:23:41.570 --> 02:23:43.840
and then after about eight hours of sleep,

02:23:43.840 --> 02:23:46.520
eight hours of sleep seems to be able to

02:23:46.520 --> 02:23:49.580
allow the brain to decrease
its adenosine levels

02:23:49.580 --> 02:23:50.900
back to normal.

02:23:50.900 --> 02:23:53.450
And so naturally, we
should start to wake up

02:23:53.450 --> 02:23:55.520
which also aligns with
your circadian rhythm.

02:23:55.520 --> 02:23:57.650
And those are two separate processes.

02:23:57.650 --> 02:24:00.710
But with about eight hours
of good quality sleep

02:24:00.710 --> 02:24:03.210
seven to nine hours for the average adult,

02:24:03.210 --> 02:24:06.210
we are free of all of that adenosine.

02:24:06.210 --> 02:24:09.010
We've evacuated it
essentially out of the brain,

02:24:09.010 --> 02:24:12.010
and we wake up naturally
feeling refreshed.

02:24:12.010 --> 02:24:14.780
The reason that naps can
be potentially dangerous

02:24:14.780 --> 02:24:16.720
is that when you nap,

02:24:16.720 --> 02:24:20.970
you are essentially opening the
valve on the pressure cooker

02:24:20.970 --> 02:24:22.600
of sleep pressure.

02:24:22.600 --> 02:24:27.540
And some of that sleepiness
is lost by way of the nap.

02:24:27.540 --> 02:24:30.109
So for some people and not all people

02:24:30.109 --> 02:24:32.340
and you're a great example of this.

02:24:32.340 --> 02:24:34.940
Some people, however,
if they are struggling

02:24:34.940 --> 02:24:37.870
with sleep at night, and
they nap during the day,

02:24:37.870 --> 02:24:40.410
it makes their sleep problems even worse.

02:24:40.410 --> 02:24:41.820
So for people with insomnia,

02:24:41.820 --> 02:24:44.880
we typically advise against napping.

02:24:44.880 --> 02:24:47.680
And the advice is if
you can nap regularly,

02:24:47.680 --> 02:24:50.130
and you don't struggle
with sleep at night,

02:24:50.130 --> 02:24:51.810
then naps are just fine.

02:24:51.810 --> 02:24:55.020
But if you do struggle with
sleep, stay away from naps.

02:24:55.020 --> 02:24:56.690
If you are going to nap,

02:24:56.690 --> 02:25:00.050
try to limit your naps,
try to cut them off a bit

02:25:00.050 --> 02:25:02.530
like sort of caffeine, maybe you know,

02:25:02.530 --> 02:25:06.150
eight to 12 hours maybe
not that you know far off

02:25:06.150 --> 02:25:09.810
maybe sort of seven to six
hours is a good rule of thumb.

02:25:09.810 --> 02:25:12.650
Try not to nap essentially
late in the afternoon.

02:25:12.650 --> 02:25:14.546
And if you do take a nap

02:25:14.546 --> 02:25:17.340
and you want to maintain your

02:25:17.340 --> 02:25:19.690
you don't want to have
that grogginess hangover

02:25:19.690 --> 02:25:21.410
that can happen after
a full night of sleep

02:25:21.410 --> 02:25:22.600
for the first hour,

02:25:22.600 --> 02:25:26.100
try to limit it to about 20, 25 minutes.

02:25:26.100 --> 02:25:27.640
And that way you don't go down

02:25:27.640 --> 02:25:30.030
into the very deepest stages of sleep,

02:25:30.030 --> 02:25:33.210
which if I wrench you
out of with an alarm,

02:25:33.210 --> 02:25:36.230
then you just kind of feel
you almost feel worse,

02:25:36.230 --> 02:25:37.940
for the first hour after the nap.

02:25:37.940 --> 02:25:40.130
- I've definitely experienced
that if I oversleep.

02:25:40.130 --> 02:25:43.130
Certainly if the sun
goes down during my nap

02:25:43.130 --> 02:25:45.060
and I wake up and light overall

02:25:45.060 --> 02:25:47.090
lighting conditions have changed,

02:25:47.090 --> 02:25:50.850
I find it very hard to jolt
myself back into the evening.

02:25:50.850 --> 02:25:52.440
And it can screw me up.

02:25:52.440 --> 02:25:54.650
So I try and keep those naps pretty brief.

02:25:54.650 --> 02:25:55.833
And I should say,

02:25:55.833 --> 02:25:59.730
I'm very happy to hear you
mention individual differences

02:25:59.730 --> 02:26:01.480
and why some people might want to nap

02:26:02.627 --> 02:26:04.326
and other people might not want to nap,

02:26:04.326 --> 02:26:06.240
I have a colleague Liqun Luo

02:26:06.240 --> 02:26:08.527
he'll be familiar to many neurobiologist.

02:26:08.527 --> 02:26:09.527
- Yeah of course.

02:26:09.527 --> 02:26:10.587
- Who's a absolutely
spectacular scientist,

02:26:10.587 --> 02:26:12.130
member of the National Academy,

02:26:12.130 --> 02:26:14.540
Howard Hughes investigator just a phenom,

02:26:14.540 --> 02:26:16.100
and has a ton of energy.

02:26:16.100 --> 02:26:18.550
But years ago, I learned

02:26:18.550 --> 02:26:21.080
that he always takes a
nap in the afternoon,

02:26:21.080 --> 02:26:23.366
so much so that when he travels

02:26:23.366 --> 02:26:24.450
to give seminars at other universities,

02:26:24.450 --> 02:26:27.297
he will tell his post lunch host

02:26:29.670 --> 02:26:31.520
whoever it is that he's
supposed to meet with,

02:26:31.520 --> 02:26:34.360
may I have your office
for 30 minutes of our,

02:26:34.360 --> 02:26:38.203
sometimes 30 minute discussion
or 60 minute discussion,

02:26:38.203 --> 02:26:39.036
because I like to take a nap.

02:26:39.036 --> 02:26:39.869
And he does that

02:26:39.869 --> 02:26:40.890
and then gives us his,

02:26:41.758 --> 02:26:42.591
his talks are typically in the afternoon

02:26:42.591 --> 02:26:43.860
in academic culture.

02:26:43.860 --> 02:26:48.860
And he describes the
effect of the nap for him

02:26:48.880 --> 02:26:50.240
this short naps in the afternoon

02:26:50.240 --> 02:26:52.210
being so profound for his productivity.

02:26:52.210 --> 02:26:54.267
That's actually what inspired me

02:26:54.267 --> 02:26:56.260
to start feeling okay
about my desire to nap.

02:26:56.260 --> 02:26:57.610
And so I think for me,

02:26:57.610 --> 02:27:00.850
that was great vindication for
those that might feel guilty

02:27:00.850 --> 02:27:02.170
about wanting a nap.

02:27:02.170 --> 02:27:04.863
But I take to heart your note about

02:27:04.863 --> 02:27:07.600
avoiding naps if you have trouble falling

02:27:07.600 --> 02:27:08.433
and staying asleep,

02:27:08.433 --> 02:27:10.430
'cause I think that I have family members

02:27:10.430 --> 02:27:13.390
who also if they nap, they're
a wreck, they can't sleep.

02:27:13.390 --> 02:27:14.970
- Yeah, I think it's just,

02:27:14.970 --> 02:27:17.830
we've often been very pro sleep

02:27:17.830 --> 02:27:19.340
with sort of the sleep community.

02:27:19.340 --> 02:27:22.200
So I think it's good to always point out

02:27:22.200 --> 02:27:25.326
these potential dark sides of any aspect.

02:27:25.326 --> 02:27:26.810
But you're absolutely right,

02:27:26.810 --> 02:27:29.180
no one should feel guilty
about getting the sleep

02:27:29.180 --> 02:27:30.740
that they need.

02:27:30.740 --> 02:27:33.750
And I think that's been one
of the big problems in society

02:27:33.750 --> 02:27:36.950
society has stigmatized
sleep with these labels

02:27:36.950 --> 02:27:38.762
of being slothful or lazy.

02:27:38.762 --> 02:27:40.920
And we're almost embarrassed, you know,

02:27:40.920 --> 02:27:43.980
to tell colleagues that we take a nap.

02:27:43.980 --> 02:27:48.380
I think sleep is a write of human beings.

02:27:48.380 --> 02:27:51.990
And I therefore think that
sleep is a civil right

02:27:51.990 --> 02:27:53.700
of all human beings.

02:27:53.700 --> 02:27:56.350
And no one should make you feel unproud

02:27:56.350 --> 02:27:58.100
of getting the sleep that you need.

02:27:58.957 --> 02:28:00.063
- No, I love that.

02:28:00.063 --> 02:28:01.485
And I it's an important point.

02:28:01.485 --> 02:28:04.110
I also feel that one of the best ways

02:28:05.903 --> 02:28:08.540
to beat your competition in any
endeavor is to outlive them.

02:28:08.540 --> 02:28:12.400
So now that we know that
sleep can enhance longevity

02:28:12.400 --> 02:28:14.995
and lack of sleep can shorten one's life,

02:28:14.995 --> 02:28:17.903
that's all the
justification I need anyway.

02:28:18.950 --> 02:28:22.140
Can somebody sleep too much?

02:28:22.140 --> 02:28:23.990
Is it possible to get too much sleep?

02:28:25.390 --> 02:28:27.440
- It's a very good question.

02:28:27.440 --> 02:28:30.710
And there are probably two
things to say about it,

02:28:30.710 --> 02:28:33.793
there is a condition
that we call hypersomnia.

02:28:34.710 --> 02:28:36.260
But that's a mixture of things,

02:28:36.260 --> 02:28:37.760
it's where people have either

02:28:37.760 --> 02:28:40.150
a very high sleep need,

02:28:40.150 --> 02:28:43.160
or they are very sleepy during the day.

02:28:43.160 --> 02:28:44.617
And they're typically falling asleep.

02:28:44.617 --> 02:28:46.620
And these can happen in a variety

02:28:47.513 --> 02:28:48.600
of different clinical contexts.

02:28:48.600 --> 02:28:51.050
One of the places where we've often seen

02:28:51.050 --> 02:28:56.050
hypersomnia believed to
manifest is in depression.

02:28:56.250 --> 02:28:58.620
But if you look at some of those studies,

02:28:58.620 --> 02:29:00.710
it turns out, it looks more as though

02:29:00.710 --> 02:29:04.610
those people are simply
reporting being in bed longer,

02:29:04.610 --> 02:29:08.040
but not necessarily sleeping longer.

02:29:08.040 --> 02:29:10.210
And that fits very well
with one of the profiles

02:29:10.210 --> 02:29:12.130
that we know of depression,

02:29:12.130 --> 02:29:13.380
which is anhedonia,

02:29:13.380 --> 02:29:15.750
you don't get pleasure from
normally pleasurable things.

02:29:15.750 --> 02:29:17.890
So you just don't want
to go out into the world,

02:29:17.890 --> 02:29:19.810
you don't want to interact
because you're depressed.

02:29:19.810 --> 02:29:20.750
So what do you do?

02:29:20.750 --> 02:29:21.920
You just stay in bed?

02:29:21.920 --> 02:29:24.334
- Blinds closed, watching
TV, on the phone.

02:29:24.334 --> 02:29:25.570
- [Matthew] Right, and that
just looks as though you know,

02:29:25.570 --> 02:29:26.780
- Felling miserable.
- When people say,

02:29:26.780 --> 02:29:28.270
what time did you go to bed?

02:29:28.270 --> 02:29:30.710
And what time did you get out of bed?

02:29:30.710 --> 02:29:32.970
The mistake made in that question is

02:29:32.970 --> 02:29:34.670
okay, that's how much time their sleeping

02:29:34.670 --> 02:29:35.970
when you should have said,

02:29:35.970 --> 02:29:37.197
what time did you fall asleep?

02:29:37.197 --> 02:29:39.040
And what time did you wake up?

02:29:39.040 --> 02:29:41.270
And the answer could be very different.

02:29:41.270 --> 02:29:45.683
So that's hypersomnia
from a clinical context.

02:29:46.890 --> 02:29:49.330
Can you sleep too much though?

02:29:49.330 --> 02:29:52.400
One of the data points that
argues yes, that's possible

02:29:52.400 --> 02:29:54.770
is when we look at all cause mortality.

02:29:54.770 --> 02:29:56.480
Certainly what you find is that

02:29:56.480 --> 02:29:59.090
using the sweet spot
of seven to nine hours,

02:29:59.090 --> 02:30:01.630
when you start to draw below seven hours,

02:30:01.630 --> 02:30:03.570
there is a relationship, which suggests

02:30:03.570 --> 02:30:04.680
that the shorter your sleep,

02:30:04.680 --> 02:30:05.690
the shorter your life.

02:30:05.690 --> 02:30:08.800
Short sleep in that regard
predicts all cause mortality.

02:30:08.800 --> 02:30:10.780
But it's again, not a linear relationship

02:30:10.780 --> 02:30:13.100
like the one that we've
seen with REM sleep.

02:30:13.100 --> 02:30:15.360
Once you get past nine hours,

02:30:15.360 --> 02:30:18.200
the mortality curve stops going down.

02:30:18.200 --> 02:30:20.670
And then once you get
further 10 or 11 hours,

02:30:20.670 --> 02:30:23.670
it hooks back up again,
it's almost like a J shape,

02:30:23.670 --> 02:30:26.290
tilted over a little bit and reversed.

02:30:26.290 --> 02:30:29.530
So there's this strange
hook, what's going on here?

02:30:29.530 --> 02:30:32.110
Right now, sleep science has at least

02:30:32.110 --> 02:30:35.350
two non mutually exclusive
explanations for this.

02:30:35.350 --> 02:30:38.600
The first is that if you look
at some of those populations,

02:30:38.600 --> 02:30:43.600
the idea is that the whatever
was causing them illness

02:30:43.710 --> 02:30:46.650
and took their lives was just too much

02:30:46.650 --> 02:30:47.980
for sleep to deal with.

02:30:47.980 --> 02:30:50.370
However, we know that when we get sick,

02:30:50.370 --> 02:30:51.870
one of the things that we do immediately

02:30:51.870 --> 02:30:54.680
in this whole mechanism
and inflammatory mechanisms

02:30:54.680 --> 02:30:57.530
cytokine mediated, when we get sick,

02:30:57.530 --> 02:30:58.440
we want to sleep more.

02:30:58.440 --> 02:31:01.793
We just want to curl up in bed
and you know, sleep it off.

02:31:03.647 --> 02:31:04.740
So the argument there is that

02:31:04.740 --> 02:31:07.970
it's not that sleep was
killing people prematurely,

02:31:07.970 --> 02:31:10.950
it was that these people
were calling on this

02:31:10.950 --> 02:31:12.010
the help of sleep,

02:31:12.010 --> 02:31:13.730
they were calling on this thing called

02:31:13.730 --> 02:31:17.120
the Swiss Army Knife of
health, that is sleep.

02:31:17.120 --> 02:31:19.300
But whatever it is that they were facing

02:31:19.300 --> 02:31:23.660
was just too powerful
for sleep to overcome.

02:31:23.660 --> 02:31:25.980
So it artificially looks as though

02:31:25.980 --> 02:31:29.450
more sleep leads to a
higher risk of death,

02:31:29.450 --> 02:31:32.660
when sleep is actually
responding to the mortality risk,

02:31:32.660 --> 02:31:33.790
and it lost the battle.

02:31:33.790 --> 02:31:35.430
That's one argument.

02:31:35.430 --> 02:31:39.230
The second is that we
know that sleep quality

02:31:39.230 --> 02:31:41.670
and poor sleep efficiency

02:31:41.670 --> 02:31:45.260
is a very strong predictor
of all cause mortality.

02:31:45.260 --> 02:31:48.320
And when you look at
people who often report

02:31:48.320 --> 02:31:49.760
sleeping longer amounts,

02:31:49.760 --> 02:31:51.310
10 or 11 hours,

02:31:51.310 --> 02:31:54.780
they typically report having
very poor quality sleep.

02:31:54.780 --> 02:31:57.280
So because their quality of sleep is poor,

02:31:57.280 --> 02:31:59.440
they just try to sleep longer

02:31:59.440 --> 02:32:01.780
to try and get some of that back.

02:32:01.780 --> 02:32:05.330
So again, here now it's poor quality sleep

02:32:05.330 --> 02:32:08.720
masking as too much sleep

02:32:08.720 --> 02:32:11.350
leading to this artificial hook

02:32:11.350 --> 02:32:12.890
which looks like mortality.

02:32:12.890 --> 02:32:14.390
That's the second explanation.

02:32:15.480 --> 02:32:17.090
A third which is more of a Gedanken,

02:32:17.090 --> 02:32:19.460
which is just the kind of
like a thought experiment

02:32:19.460 --> 02:32:21.600
and I have this mentality,

02:32:21.600 --> 02:32:24.560
